  "local_port": 59772,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do i (a Java developer) get an Adobe Experience Manager (AEM) instance for learning the CMS? I'm not Adobe Parner.",
  "response": "As a Java developer looking to learn Adobe Experience Manager (AEM), you have a few options even if you're not an Adobe Partner:\n\n### 1. **Adobe's Trial or Sandbox Environment**\nAdobe sometimes provides trial versions or sandbox environments where you can explore and learn AEM. While these options might not always be publicly advertised, you can try directly contacting Adobe or checking their website for any trial offers.\n\n#### Steps:\n- Visit the official [Adobe Experience Manager](https://business.adobe.com/products/experience-manager/adobe-experience-manager.html) page.\n- Look for trial or demo options.\n- Contact Adobe sales or support directly and inquire about trial, sandbox environments, or any available educational resources.\n\n### 2. **Adobe Experience League**\nAdobe Experience League is a platform designed to help users learn and get certified in Adobe products, including AEM. It offers tutorials, documentation, and sometimes access to environments where you can practice.\n\n#### Steps:\n- Go to [Adobe Experience League](https://experienceleague.adobe.com/?lang=en).\n- Sign up for an account if you don't already have one.\n- Search for AEM learning modules, tutorials, and possibly access to practice environments.\n\n### 3. **Community and Open Source Projects**\nThere are various community-driven solutions and open-source projects that replicate AEM functionality to some extent. They can provide a starting point for learning the overall concepts and development practices used in AEM.\n\n#### Examples:\n- **WCM.io**: Open-source components for AEM.\n  - Visit [wcm.io](https://wcm.io/)\n- **ACS AEM Commons**: Community tools, components, and extensions for AEM.\n  - Visit [ACS AEM Commons GitHub](https://github.com/Adobe-Consulting-Services/acs-aem-commons)\n\n### 4. **Local Development with Adobe AEM SDK**\nAdobe provides an SDK for local development. This is particularly useful for developers wanting to get a hands-on experience with AEM on their local machines.\n\n#### Steps:\n- Visit the [Adobe I/O SDK downloads page](https://developer.adobe.com/aem/downloads/).\n- Download the AEM SDK.\n- Follow the instructions for setting up AEM locally, ensuring your system meets the prerequisites.\n\n### 5. **Online Learning Platforms**\nSome online learning platforms offer courses specifically on AEM. Websites like Udemy, Pluralsight, and LinkedIn Learning might have relevant courses.\n\n#### Steps:\n- Go to your preferred learning platform.\n- Search for AEM courses.\n- Enroll in courses that cover the basics and advanced topics.\n\n### 6. **User Groups and Forums**\nParticipating in forums such as Stack Overflow, Adobe Community, and other developer-centric groups can provide insights and sometimes information about how to access AEM for practice purposes.\n\n#### Steps:\n- Join relevant forums and communities.\n- Actively participate and ask about AEM practice environments.\n\n### 7. **Company's Internal Resources**\nIf you\u2019re employed in an organization that utilizes AEM, you might have access to internal training resources, staging environments, or sandbox instances. Speak with your employer or IT department to see if you can get access for learning purposes.\n\n#### Steps:\n- Contact your IT department or manager.\n- Request access to any development or staging instances of AEM.\n\nBy exploring these options, you should be able to find a way to get hands-on experience with Adobe Experience Manager and begin learning the CMS effectively.",
